description: Very cool auroras last night. They were coming over the mountains in waves. It only lasted around an hour. It was around -30F with the windchill. If the show lasted any longer I probably would have frostbite, because I wasn't going anywhere until it was done.

description: A pretty incredible night. I normally don't like to shoot northern lights when the moon is out, because the moonlight will usually make the auroras less vibrant and harder to see. This was one of my only photos with a tinge of red.

description: - www.kevin-palmer.com - The aurora display only lasted a couple hours on this night before a snow storm moved in. But it was very bright and active. I shot most of it from a frozen pond a few minutes outside of Fairbanks. Methane bubbles were suspended in the ice.
title: Aurora and Methane Bubbles

description: - www.kevin-palmer.com - At the end of October I had the the chance to spend a week in Alaska. I timed this trip with the arrival of a solar wind stream so the northern lights would be extra active. The sky only stayed clear for a couple hours on this night, but that was enough to see this bright ¡¥aurora rainbow.¡¦ Only by shooting a panorama with my widest lens could I capture all of it. Most of the lakes and wetlands around Fairbanks had these bubbles in them. They are made of methane gas suspended in the ice. Just 30-40 cm underground is the permafrost, which normally stays frozen year round. But as the Arctic warms and the permafrost thaws, the decaying plant matter (also known as peat) releases methane into the atmosphere. During the summer this gas is invisible. But for a short time after the water freezes and before it gets covered with snow, these frozen bubbles are visible. Many area lakes have such a high concentration of methane that it¡¦s actually possible to pop these bubbles and light them on fire.
title: Rainbow of Aurora

description: - www.kevin-palmer.com - The aurora display only lasted a couple hours on this night before a snow storm moved in. But it was very bright and active. I shot most of it from a frozen pond a few minutes outside of Fairbanks. Methane bubbles were suspended in the ice.

A special thanks to my friend Joe who assisted with excellent advice on shots and settings. Always great to learn new things in this hobby. Eagle Harbor, MI September 28, 2019. description:
Binnshire, Gouldsboro, Maine

I was out shooting a poorly developed Aurora with my Nikon when I decided, due to lack of results, to play with my new Olympus TG-6. This is the "Live Composite" mode and is interesting. It doesn't seem that any mode is particularly good at starry skies. Instead the various Nightscape modes seem to be for city night light levels. It could be that the TG-6 sensor just isn't up to it, or it could be that I just haven't figured it out yet. If someone has TG-5 or TG-6 settings that work for them for dark night sky and astro-photography, please pass them along via comment or private message.
title: Night sky via Olympus TG-6

description:
Binnshire, Gouldsboro, Maine.

I received more color in the sky when I light painted the shore. Not sure how much sky color is Aurora and how much is the remainder of sunset (thought this is pointing North).

In the future I would do better to use a higher ISO and shorten the exposure in order to get sharper stars with less arc. Of course it would be nice to use a faster lens but my 50mm f1.2, while very fast, isn't wide enough and, being old school from my old F3 days, is strictly manual and takes some setup in the camera.
title: Aurora, but a weak one

description: One of the things a friend and I had while see while staying at the North Face Lodge (along with many others too!) was to have a chance to experience an aurora under the dark skies in this portion of the national park. Not so lucky on the first night, given the overcast skies that we would have the following day. Later that afternoon, the skies cleared and there was a report of significant solar activity that might lead to a northern lights show. A friend and I went to bed and were awoken shortly afterwards and told rush outside for an amazing experience! There's still much that I have to learn with how long of a shutter speed and getting a ¡§right¡¨ focus. This was during one of the peaks of the aurora show that evening with a view looking to the east.
title: Standing Under a Light Show Over the Skies of Denali National Park & Preserve

description:
No, this is not the Northern Lights, or the Aurora Borealis.  Just clouds moving overhead.  Even though the Northern Lights are projected to be seen this week-end as far down as Michigan or along the northern latitude States in the US.  However, there has been several rare occasions that the lights have been seen from Alabama.  I do remember seeing the Northern Lights from Camp Hill, Alabama back in 1979 or 80.  It almost look just like this image with the naked eye.   

Blount Mountain, County Road 24, Oneonta, Blount County, Alabama.  August 31, 2019 at 2049.

P2019-0831T204943
Canon EOS Rebel T6i
Lens:  Canon EF-S18-135mm f/3.5-5.6 IS 
Focal Length: 18mm
ISO: 400
Exposure: 68 seconds at f/5.6
title: Not The Northen Lights

description: Using my Timelapse+ VIEW I shot this up at the Alexian Brothers Novitiate in Gresham Wi. This is 351 shots stacked into a star trail from my last Northern Lights showing. This might be the best star trail I've gotten with the aurora yet. If you would like to see the actual timelapse it's in this timelapse. www.youtube.com/watch?v=gzUNtJC6t8k Canon 6D Mark II Rokinon 24mm Timelapse+VIEW f/1.4 ISO6400 8 sec www.instagram.com/UH82NVME
title: Alexian Brothers Novitiate Aurora Startrail

description: All the stars aligned (quite literally) for me on this one. I rarely get lucky enough to plan a trip somewhere and have something like THIS happen. It almost never fails to have clouds and rain! I haven't seen a good showing of the northern lights in quite a long time but my visit to the Alexian Brothers Novitiate definitely did NOT disappoint!! I wish I would have had my wider lens on but that one was running a timelapse. :) Although, with 24mm you get to see the big and little dipper in all their glory with the beautiful northern lights!! Canon 6D Mark II Rokinon 24mm f/1.4 f/1.4 8 sec ISO 6400 www.instagram.com/UH82NVME
title: Alexian Brothers Novitiate Northern Lights

description:
The night had turned chilly after a warm day. The lake was misting over and the aurora was just starting to make a light appearance as per the light glow on the horizon on the right side of the image. It was a beautiful night for taking pictures!

This series of trails was shot over a span of just under 1 hour. I was planning on going longer, but the aurora flared up and that would have washed out the background in greens, yellows and purples, ruining my trails.
title: Foggy Trails

description:
In the early morning hours of August 5th, an aurora erupted that was easily seen as far south as our region of South Eastern Ontario. What was predicted to be a fairly low intensity geomagnetic storm birthed some sub-storms beyond what had been expected, sending shimmering bands of green rippling above the horizon. As Lady Aurora danced for me, veils of purple light rolled across the sky as giant columns amidst the shimmer and whipping around of the greens. While this spectacle played out above, wisps of mist rose from the lake, enveloping the area in an eerie fog. 

Shot at Camden Lake Provincial Wildlife Park near Moscow in beautiful Lennox and Addington County in South Eastern Ontario, Canada.
title: ?? Smoke on the Water & Fire In The Sky ??
Parliament Hill - Centre Block at Night

description: The Laurentian Divide separates the river systems that flow northwards to the Arctic Ocean and Hudson Bay from those that flow southwards to the Atlantic Ocean, Caribbean Sea and Gulf of Mexico. On this night, it offered an overlook to the north as we caught a glimpse of the aurora. A persistent area of clouds just to our north necessitated a run further up the Gunflint Trail, trying to get around the west edge. This whole area is devoid of cell phone coverage, so we really had no idea what the aurora was doing, if anything at all. In this view, the Canadian border is a mere two miles away. Near Birch Lake, MN on March 14, 2018. SOURCE FILE 5611 Copyright All my photographic and video images are copyrighted. All rights are reserved. description:
A fish-eye lens view of an all-sky aurora on February 16, 2018, over the Churchill Northern Studies Centre, in Churchill, Manitoba, and caught during a short-lived bright outburst when the bottom fringe of the auroral curtains turned brilliant pink for a minute or so, due to energetic electrons exciting lower altitude nitrogen molecules. 

This was with the 8mm Sigma fish-eye lens at f/3.5 and the Canon 6D MkII at ISO 3200. The sky is one exposure while the ground is a mean combined stack of 5 exposures to smooth noise. The exposures were part of a 925-frame time-lapse.
title: All-Sky Aurora with Pink Curtains #1

description: This night was supposed to be a really good one for Aurora based on the sun's activity, so I went out in search of the light. I find that the most reliable aurora displays usually occur after midnight, but as I had to work in the morning, I was out before 10pm. This photo is the result. I used the Olympus OM-D E-M1 with the M.Zuiko 7-14mm f/2.8. The camera was set to Live Composite and this photo was the result of a little over 15 minutes of composite exposures. The star trails were an added bonus of the long exposure time.
title: Aurora and Star Trails

description:
While sitting in front of a warm campfire at New England Outdoor Center, I set up my camera a few feet away to shoot a timelapse of the Aurora Borealis over Mt. Katahdin and Millinocket Lake on October 12, 2017, 00:15. Vega shines brightly to the left and a 54% moon lit the mountain and pine trees.

Camera settings: 24mm, f/2.8, ISO 5000, 20 seconds for the sky and f/2.8, ISO 800, 510 seconds for the foreground.

Equipment used: Nikon D850, Nikon 14-24mm f/2.8, and Really Right Stuff TVC-34L tripod & BH-55 ballhead. Edited in Lightroom, blended in Photoshop.
title: Aurora over Mount Katahdin

description: This is one of my all-time favorites. A very active aurora developed during the evening twilight. The combination led to a color explosion in the sky leading to a rare set up of blue, purple, and green vertical pillars spiking through 2 horizontal green bands of light and the orange glow of twilight. All of this occurred over the remnants of a shipwreck at Whitefish Point, Michigan. A solar storm flared up in the sky right at twilight and continued non-stop for 6+ hours along the Lake Superior coastline at Whitefish Point on October 11-12th 2017. www.rossellet.com
title: Twilight Solar Storm

description: Seeing auroras much further north than I usually do was quite an experience- for most of the time at lower latitudes the arc can be a bit dim and you count on the occasional substorm to liven things up. My basic go-to exposure is ISO 1000, F2.8, and 30-sec. If there is a moon out it can certainly wash things out...this particular image during a fantastic substorm illustrates the difference- this is ISO800, F2.8, and four seconds. Some of the cloud illumination at upper right is from a 70% moon just out of the frame. Probably should have dropped the ISO even more and balanced that with a slightly longer exposure, but I'll take this result. Along the bottom of the aurora it was literally zipping around the sky, green underlined with pink. Bucket-list type material here...one only wonders what the (few) people in the neighboring cabins thought about all the crazy people out on the shore yelling at 0330 in the morning... Gull Harbour, Hecla Island, Manitoba, Canada. October 11, 2017. Copyright All my photographic and video images are copyrighted. All rights are reserved. description: You know it's about to get good when the aurora coalesces into a high, bright arc. Some pillars dance in the distance on the low horizon...and amazing reflection in the water on this one. And if you look closely, you can see the rocks underwater about 10-15 feet offshore! The double satellite trail in the upper right is possibly one of the US Navy's secretive NOSS clusters- these show up regularly in my night sky images. Another possibility is the Iridium replacement program, in which the new satellite shadows the old one prior to it being de-orbited. en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naval_Ocean_Surveillance_System Hecla Island, Manitoba, Canada October 11, 2017. description: This photo was taken with the Olympus OM-D E-M1 and M.Zuiko 7-14mm f/2.8 Pro. I stopped down the lens to f/3.5 to obtain enough DOF to compensate for any minor focus errors that might have occurred in the pitch black conditions. Camera was mounted on a tripod and I utilized the OM-D's Livetime facility to monitor the exposure in real time. ISO was kept at 200 and I used a three-plus minute exposure to obtain this image. I painted the near trees with an LED flashlight to provide some foreground interest.
title: Northern Lights over McIntyre Creek

description: My original plan when I picked up a workshop participant at 3am was to head to Bow Lake to capture the Milky Way in pitch-black skies; however, after watching the northern lights dancing in front of us for the whole drive from Banff, we decided to head up to the Bow Summit (where there is a clear view to the north) instead. This is what we were greeted with -- dancing greens and purples and lights pulsing across the entire sky. I think it was the right choice! title: Pemaquid Aurora

description:
My last night in the Yukon.  I'd been waiting for a light show for the whole trip, and the sky just didn't permit any aurora photography.  Whether it was the cloud cover, being too far north to see real darkness, or low solar activity, I was just not having any success.  In all honesty, it was a very familiar feeling - I often go Aurora hunting in Southern Ontario, and even on the days where I'm relatively confident that I'll see something, I am used to coming home empty handed.

On our very last night in the Yukon, my travel companion happened to take one last look out of our hotel window to see green in the sky, and was kind enough to wake me up!  We rushed to the nearest location we thought would make for an interesting foreground (Miles Canyon in Whitehorse) based on our limited knowledge of the area.  While the light show may not have been outrageous for Whitehorse standards, it was far ahead of the aurora I'm used to seeing in Southern Ontario.  No matter how you look at it, I couldn't think of a better way to finish my trip to the Yukon this year.

This photo was taken with a Canon 5D IV, and a Rokinon 14mm f/2.8.  This is a two image composite - one short exposure for the sky immediately followed by one longer exposure for the foreground.  Processed in Camera Raw and Photoshop.

[Edit: A late Explore addition - highest position - #8]
title: From the River to the Sky

description:
My last night in the Yukon.  Now, I've seen the northern lights in Southern Ontario several times, but it has never been anything like this light show.  Not having a lot of time to make decisions on where to shoot, we chose to re-visit what we knew - Miles Canyon in Whitehorse.  As soon as we picked this location, I had this composition in mind, even before I got out of the car.  Lucky for me, the lights decided to cooperate wth that vision!  What a special treat this was.

Shot on a Canon 5D IV with a Rokinon 14mm f/2.8.  Processed in Camera Raw and Photoshop from two exposures - one short(ish) exposure to catch some movement in the aurora, and one long(ish) exposure to fully expose the foreground.  Neat!
title: Spirits Over the River

description: Conditions for this Milky Way Panorama workshop were already good and on this last night at Delicate Arch, we were super fortunate to see Aurora Borealis. But this was just the prelude¡K the real show got started soon after this sequence was captured. What a thrill that was! My training partner, Darren White and I have just two more big events to go and we'll wind up our 2017 workshop season. With arcing Milky Way panoramas and Aurora Borealis and a cloud inversion and a big boatload of awesome students, this season was one for the history books! If you weren't part of the incredible experience this year, make sure to stay tuned for the 2018 schedule when it's released on December 1st from NightPhotographyWorkshop.com.

description:
I have wanted to camp at Stormhaven back country camp site in Bruce Peninsula National Park for years, but I never guessed that I would get this kind of show on my first stay.  What a sight this was.  Probably the strongest northern lights I've ever seen from this park.  Can't help but feel lucky in witnessing it!

Photographed using a Canon 6D and a Rokanon 14mm f/2.8.  This image is a composite of two images, one for the foreground and one for the sky.  Processed using Camera Raw and Photoshop.
title: The Storm at Stormhaven

description:
Once in a while, if you're patient, you can see the northern lights in southern Ontario.  When that opportunity arrises, I usually try to find the darkest skies possible, and stick around until the weather cooperates.  On this particular night, there was absolutely no argument from the weather.  I shot all night, and this was my last opportunity to capture the northern lights before dawn. I took the opportunity to try and get a bit more creative, and bring a human element into the image.  In the end, it was quite the sight to behold, I only hope I was able to convey that with this image!

This image was shot using a Canon 6D and Rokanon 14mm f/2.8.  The image is a composite from 3 images (one for sky, one for foreground texture, one for contrast in the light on the rocks).  Processed in Camera Raw and Photoshop.
title: That Evening Glow

description:
I have to admit, there are moments when I head out to take photos that absolutely make me feel small and insignificant in the presence of our natural world.  This was one of those nights.

I have been dreaming of creating an image like this for a long time, and this was the first time that the "stars aligned" to let me get a reasonable chance at it.  Bruce Peninsula National Park, a dark sky preserve, has some great opportunities for seeing the night sky in all its glory.  It's one of the many reasons I frequent the park!

I chose this night for the photo because I was confidant that the sky would be moonless and clear, but I did not expect the northern lights to come out, and I completely missed the fact that this was the peak of the lyrid meteor shower!  I feel truly lucky to have witnessed the sky that night.  If you look close, you'll find a number of shooting stars, and a lot of iridium flares.

This image was captured using a Canon 6D and a Rokanon 14mm f/2.8.  The image is a composite of 26 photos (two rows of 13) covering over 180 degrees of view.  The image was stitched together in PTGui Pro, edited in Camera Raw and Photoshop.
title: From This World To The Next

description: Lots going on in this image....twilight was still casting a blue glow to the sky at this time, plus I was sitting near an intersection with artificial lighting waiting for another aurora hunter to arrive. So let's start with the obvious. There is aurora behind the trees on the left, looks like quite a bit of it in fact- that purple goes pretty high. To the right of center is a feature that has been in the news lately, as of now it doesn't have a "sciency" name....but an Alberta Aurora group coined the name "Steve" (from the movie "Over the Hedge") and so far it is sticking. The media has picked up on the story and it is getting lots of attention. What is it? Still not fully understood, but not a new thing either. Beyond that, there are at least 5 satellites visible... #steve Ely, Minnesota. March 27, 2017. Copyright All my photographic and video images are copyrighted. All rights are reserved. description: The aurora had been raging up to Kp9 most of the day peaking to an atmospheric power of over 130 GW - the strongest I've ever seen since I've been monitoring it for the last couple of years. Despite the almost full moon hanging in the sky, I decided to head out to my lucky spot at Camden Lake in beautiful Lennox and Addington County to see if I could capture it. By the time I arrived, the aurora was fading in intensity and had dropped down to an average about Kp5; great under dark skies, but not so good under a bright moon, But undaunted, I tried my luck nonetheless. Most of it was very sublime, but there was a period of about 10 minutes where it flared up brighter than anything I'd ever seen since I was a kid living up in the tundras of northern Quebec. It was bright and the purples and magentas were easily visible to the naked eye despite the bright blue sky in the background. This is 124 minutes of imaging compressed into just over 1 minute of actual time lapse footage. Camera geekery: Nikon D750 with Nikon 24-70 f/2.8 3 second exposures @ ISO 1600 Nikon D7000 with Vivitar 13mm f/2.8 5 second exposures @ ISO 1500 www.youtube.com/watch?v=LOuVZr1VNmM&feature=youtu.be
title: Time Lapse: Aurora borealis under an almost full moon

description:
Tewkesbury, Qu?bec, Canada - Automne 2016

Here is a very special picture, which requested a bit of luck to get the aurora and time for the star trails. The view is from the church in Tewkesbury, north of Quebec City. The northern lights have been slow to show up. From the beginning of the evening, I started a time lapse. My camera captured a photo every 20 seconds from 9:30 pm until 2:00 am. By stacking the pictures, I got the circular star movement effect caused by the rotation of the Earth.
---
Voici une photo bien sp?ciale, qui a demand? un brin de chance pour avoir les aurores et beaucoup de temps pour les train?es d'?toiles. La vue est celle de l'?glise ? Tewkesbury, au nord de Qu?bec. Les aurores ont mis du temps ? se pointer le bout du nez. D?s le d?but de la soir?e, j'ai d?marr? un timelapse. L'appareil a donc captur? une photo toutes les 20 secondes de 9h30 jusqu'? 2h du matin. En empilant toutes les photos, nous obtenons l'effet circulaire produit par la rotation de la Terre. Au centre de ce cercle, nous retrouvons l'?toile Polaire.

? bient?t,
Fred
title: Les aurores brillent et "les ??toiles tournent"

description: Last Fall, I planted thirteen different varieties of azaleas and rhododendrons at our Hay Bay gardens. The plants survived the winter but, unfortunately, two mid-winter thaws killed off the flower buds and I only had one bud open up this Spring. Thankfully, the same fate did not befall the azaleas at my Kanata property and this week all three plants are blooming beautifully as they have done since I planted them in 1999.
title: Azaleas in Kanata, Ontario

description: Here was the view from next to my camp site. The aurora came out around midnight to light up the sky. I'm guessing it was about -20C outside. I stood on the thin ice to take this shot. The water  wasn't  too deep under my feet. I know because I lit up the ice with my flashlight. That's why you see the turquoise glow at the bottom. One thing really freaked me out while I was on the ice. As the temperature drops and the ice freezes thicker, tension and pressure builds up in the ice. My weight on it was enough to cause a release in that tension and this loud and wide and powerful ping shot out from all around me. Made me jump out of my skin. Maybe one of the coolest sounds I've ever heard.
title: Aurora over Joffre Lake

description:
Tewkesbury, Qu?bec, Canada - Automne 2015

After a second night without northern lights luck, I must rely on October 7th photos (which are not bad auroras!). I hung out with J?r?mie LeBlond-Fontaine for the whole night. We saw several stars, we maybe saw some shy green lights and for sure, we saw many many clouds. But anyway, we had a very great night!
---
Apr?s une seconde soir?e d'espoir pour les aurores bor?ales, je dois me rabattre sur mes photos du 7 octobre dernier. Je vous partage donc une photo de Tewkesbury il y a un mois. Hier, j'ai pass? la soir?e ? l'?le d'Orl?ans avec J?r?mie LeBlond-Fontaine. Nous avons vu plusieurs ?toiles, avons possiblement entrevu quelques vagues couleurs vertes et assurment vu beaucoup de nuages. L'important est que nous avons pass?s une belle soir?e!

Bonne soir?e,
Fred

description:
Tewkesbury, Qu?bec, Canada - Automne 2015

The northern lights gave us quite a show on October 7th. This time, I gave myself a little challenge to include some hidden gems in the photo. Starting from the left is the Big Dipper at the tip of the left most aurora. Also falling into the magenta lights peak on the right, we see the northern part of the Milky Way. Finally, in the upper right corner, the great Andromeda Galaxy overlooks the landscape. To capture this vast landscape, I made a panorama of several images recombined into this photo which I'm very proud of.
---
Les aurores bor?ales nous ont donn? tout un spectacle le 7 octobre dernier. Cette fois-ci, je me suis donn? un petit d?fi d'inclure quelques joyaux cach?s dans la photo. En partant de la gauche, on voit la grande ourse ? la pointe de la petite aurore. Aussi, descendant dans le pic magenta des aurores ? droite, on voit (faiblement) la partie nord de la Voie Lact?e. Finalement, dans le coin sup?rieur droit, la grande Galaxie d'Androm?de surplombe le paysage. Afin de capturer cette immense paysage, il a fallu que je fasse un panorama de plusieurs images recombin?es en cette photo dont je suis tr?s fier.

Fred
title: Aurores bor?ales, Voie Lact?e et Androm?de

description:
I was up early Tuesday morning and went to Island View Beach for some star photos. Little did I know I would finally see the Northern Lights!

To be honest, I didn't actually see them with my own eyes.  It wasn't until I looked at the photo on the camera that I saw the green bands.
title: Aurora Borealis seen from Victoria!

description: Jarvis Lake Hinton AB Canada. This was what the northern sky looked like before I turned around and took the first Aurora shot I posted. There was a slight hint of green in the sky. It was foggy and 26 degrees. I don't know where the planets are suppose to be, but I think this is Venus.
title: Aurora Hinton AB Canada 2-

description: The night of Sept 19/20, 2015 had a pretty incredible northern lights display, despite the passing clouds.This is along the Red Deer River north of Sundre, Alberta. I started shooting at about 10:30 pm in the evening and wrapped up at about 3:00 am. What a night!
title: Sky Dance

description: This morning's amazing light show honouring the victims and heroes of 9/11. Watching the Aurora Borealis never gets old for me. I can't help but say "WOW!!" everytime I see the northern sky pulsing with waves of light. This latest one was at a storm level of 6.67 Kp and lasted for a couple of hours into dawn. description:
Aurora borealis above the Phoenix Church in Houghton Michigan. 

From Keweenaw County Historical Society: St. Mary's Church was built in 1858 to serve the Catholic residents in the nearby mining community of Cliff, scene of the area's first major copper discovery in 1844. Services continued until 1899 when the church was dismantled and reassembled in Phoenix, where it was renamed The Church of the Assumption. Masses were held until 1957, when the last service marked a century of providing spiritual guidance to mining families and their descendants.
title: God is light

description:
I'm a nerd.  When I proposed to my lovely wife, I got down on my knees in the mineral section of the Denver Museum of Natural History.  26 years later, I take her to Fairbanks, Alaska, to celebrate our anniversary under the aurora borealis.

This is the picture of use, posing under the lights.
title: Happy Anniversary Aurora

description:
I've been doing a lot of solo camping this summer. Sometimes I go far from home, other times not too far. Rain or shine - it doesn't really matter. On this night, I headed out specifically to photograph the northern lights - but forgot to check the lunar cycle. My luck - it was a Full Moon !. Even with the bright light from the full moon, the northern lights can still be seen.

Directly behind me, out of view of the  photo are the lights of Yellowknife. 
My tent is light from the inside with a flashlight. 
Nikon D700, Nikon 17-35mm lens. 8.0 second exposure, f/3.5, ISO 320. 


_SHS9055-2
title: Camping - Full Moon and Aurora

description:
Tewkesbury, Qu?bec, Canada - ?t? 2015

Cette soir?e a commenc? tellement relaxe chez moi, en pyjama ? me demander si j'allais sortir ou non. Apr?s tout, je travaillais toute la semaine. Tout ? coup, j'ai vu sur les r?seau sociaux que quelques personnes observaient de faibles lueurs. Je me suis dit que je n'allais pas manquer les aurores comme au mois de juin. ? mon arriv?e ? Tewkesbury, il n'y avait plus de lueurs, mais seulement des nuages (beaucoup de nuages!). Avec un peu de patience, nous avons eu droit ? un d?gagement qui a laiss? place ? une explosion de lumi?res. C'est officiellement le plus beau ciel de toute ma vie et je suis bien heureux de le partager avec vous!
title: Soir?e m?morable

description:
Tewkesbury, Qu?bec, Canada - ?t? 2015

Here is a photo captured this summer and chances are good that I can see them again tonight. This image is a panorama of 5 photos taken in portrait orientation with a wide angle at 21mm. It was quite an experience to see it with the naked eye. I cross my fingers to see it again!
---
Voici un souvenir de circonstance capt? ? Tewkesbury cet ?t?, car il y a des risques d'aurores ce soir. Cette photo est un panorama de 5 photos portrait grand angle ? 21mm. C'?tait toute une exp?rience de voir ?a ? l'oeil nu. Je croise mes doigts pour revoir le tout!

Fred
title: Mur lumineux

description: This is another photo from a good night under the northern lights a few months ago. I posted a pano a while back from the same night.

5-frame panorama
This was really difficult to stitch because the lights were moving very quickly and were different in each frame.  Photoshop wouldn't even come close with auto-blend.  I really liked the reflection and I didn't think that the photo did the night justice without showing the whole lake in one image, so here is my futile attempt at a northern lights panorama over Beach Lake, Alaska.
title: Beach Lake Aurora

description: We rallied a group to hike up the 5,341 ft tall, 5.4 mile round trip Mt Pilchuck Peak at Midnight to see if we could see the Aurora Borealis from the top. We made it at 2AM and got to see some green, yellow, purple and redish lights dance around on the horizon. We stuck around to witness a gorgeous sunrise and 360 degree views before heading back down.

description: Another magnetic storm is in town and this time it's all over the news. Dozens of astrophotographers make the trip up to the cove to catch a glimpse of the Aurora Borealis. This was a strong storm (8.33 Kp) and it did not disappoint. The northern lights danced in the night sky and reflected off the Howe Sound. Captured this morning at Porteau Cove Provincial Park, Squamisn-Lillooet, BC ~ 06-23-2015 1:30am www.Instagram.com/SeaSide_Signs www.Facebook.com/SeaSideSigns www.Twitter.com/SeaSideSigns www.Google.com/profiles/SeaSideSigns www.SeaSideSigns.Tumblr.com www.Pinterest.com/SeaSideSigns www.About.me/SeaSide_Signs www.SeaSideSigns.com

description: A strange red/magenta auroral arc overhead across the sky, with a more normal green diffuse glow to the north, as seen on May 10, 2015. The Big Dipper is overhead in the centre of the frame, Jupiter is at left in the west and Arcturus is at top to the south. I shot this from home, using an 8mm fish-eye lens to take in most of the sky, with the camera looking north. It is part of a 170-frame time-lapse sequence. Exposure was 32 seconds at f/3.5 and ISO 3200 with the Canon 6D. For a time-lapse movie of the aurora go to amazingsky.net/2015/05/11/the-red-aurora-of-may-10/
title: Red Auroral Arc #3 (May 10, 2015)

description: A strange red/magenta auroral arc overhead across the sky, with a more normal green diffuse glow to the north, as seen on May 10, 2015, in a stack of 80 frames taken over 45 minutes. The Big Dipper is overhead in the centre of the frame, Jupiter is at left in the west and Arcturus is at top to the south. I shot this from home, using an 8mm fish-eye lens to take in most of the sky, with the camera looking north. The 80 exposures were stacked and blended with Advanced Stacker Actions from StarCircleAcademy.com using the Long Trails effect. Each exposure was 32 seconds at f/3.5 and ISO 3200 with the Canon 6D. An individual exposure adds the more point-like stars at the start of the tapered star trails, and add the blue from the last twilight glow still illuminating the sky at the start of the sequence. For a time-lapse movie of the aurora go to amazingsky.net/2015/05/11/the-red-aurora-of-may-10/
title: All-Sky Aurora & Circumpolar Star Trails

description: A magnificent multicolored aurora is reflected by the frozen surface of Nutirwik Creek, in the Brooks Range of northern Alaska, just past midnight on March 21, 2015. Aurora occur when fast-moving charged particles from the sun are directed by the Earth's magnetic field to the polar regions, where they strike molecules in the atmosphere and cause them to emit light.
title: Aurora - Nutirwik Creek, Brooks Range, Alaska

description: What a sight! We have been planning a backpacking trip to the Porcupine Mountains for several months. We picked late September for the combination of peak fall color and the higher aurora chances near the new moon. We got a lot more than we expected. We ditched the tent and set our alarm each hour to see if the lights were out. The sky was cloudy most of the night, but at 3:30am there wasn't a cloud in the sky. We made our way to the lakeshore and sure enough the northern lights were dim on the northern horizon. At one point you could hear the howl of a distant wolf pack while the northern lights were out. Then moments later a slow move fireball flashed across the sky. It lasted a couple seconds and the brightness pulsed as it moved through the atmosphere. After that the aurora faded, but several more meteors (some very bright) streaked above us. The aurora was even brighter the following night which kept dozens of backcountry campers up with excitement. Picture was taken on September 26th at 3:49am EDT. My Nikon D7000 was set to f/1.8 with an ISO of 3200 on my 35mm lens. The image is not cropped and it is a 13 second exposure.
title: Aurora Fireball

description:
Traveling through the Yukon wilderness earlier this year presented me with many wonderful opportunities to photography the Northern Lights. As I was traveling with a group of hunters, the opportunities became somewhat more ¡§unique¡¨ as the expedition progressed.

The hunters were after moose, and they were successful in their efforts. This presented me with a photographic subject to experiment with. Using an antler from one of the moose, I was able to create a fun composition with a fisheye lens and the auroras dancing in the sky in the background. It was a fun experiment and I like the results!

This was a tricky shot to take. I needed to let plenty of light in, while still maintaining a decent depth of field. Fisheye lenses will always have a very large depth of field, but I needed to find the right balance to get a clear and usable image. It didn¡¦t help that my Canon EF 15mm F/2.8 fisheye lens was broken, and couldn¡¦t work reliably at anything beyond its maximum aperture! By pure luck I was able to get a few shots off at F/4 without generating an ¡§Error 01¡¨ and requiring the camera to reboot. It¡¦s not the first time my camera gear has failed in the field, but I¡¦m glad I was still able to salvage some great images. :)

Looking back over my adventures in September and October, I have many image still to edit, and some great stories to share. With ¡§snowflake season¡¨ quickly approaching, I¡¦ll be sure to get a few in before other projects take up all of my time.

What are your thoughts on this? I¡¦m sure the image will mean different things to different people. I personally would never be able to shoot an animal, but I¡¦m glad I was able to make my own use of hunt for creative photography.?
title: Yukon Silhouette

description:
Clear nights in the Yukon wilderness hold a certain magic I have not seen anywhere else. A total lack of light pollution reveals more stars in the sky than I have ever seen before, but the beauty only begins with the stars. The auroras seen dancing across the sky are more beautiful than I could have imagined. View large!

The field of view in this image is incredibly wide ¡V 180 degrees with a fisheye lens. I manually correct for the horizon distortion so that I don¡¦t lose any stars in the sky, or any of the strikingly green curtains. Most of the sky was filled with faint colours, periodically erupting into shimmering and dancing displays of light. It¡¦s hard not to be inspired.

I was traveling for a little more than two weeks in the wilderness, and thankfully had the opportunity to photograph the auroras on a number of occasions. Most clear nights there was something to photograph in the sky, even if it was too dim to see with your own eyes. I¡¦d often set up the camera to capture time-lapse video and head to bed, with the camera clicking away until the batteries drained at some point during the night. I have never felt a greater motivation to get out of bed than the morning after a shoot like this, to review the footage and see what spontaneous bursts of solar energy were captured in the frame.

It¡¦s not likely that I¡¦ll go back soon, but I hope I get another chance to photograph the auroras again. It¡¦s like a constantly evolving painting in the heavens.?
title: Fountain of the Heavens

description:
I decided to do something experimental ¡V combine nearly 700 images originally shot as time-lapse footage of the Northern Lights into a single frame. This is the result.
 
Exactly an hour and a half of footage illustrates all the paths the aurora took across the sky. Shot with a fisheye lens and with post-processing to straighten the horizon, the top of the frame is actually behind the camera. The entire sky was illuminated with dancing green curtains of light.
 
The exposure for an image like this is tricky. Auroras can flare up for intensely bright displays while the rest of the time the dancing lights remain dim. Not wanting the brighter exposures to clip, I intentionally underexposed all of the frames. When the most active moments of the aurora came, I was able to recover the highlights and include them in the final composite.
 
Combining frames like this can be tricky ¡V I knew I wanted to work with 16-bit TIFF data, and loading 693 TIFF files into Photoshop would bring almost every computer to its knees. Without performing any operations in Photoshop, my computer was utilizing 98GB of RAM. Thankfully the monster computer I built has 128GB of DDR3 memory (and 24 processor cores / 48 threads) so I didn¡¦t run into any issues. I¡¦m actually quite impressed how Photoshop handled it.
 
Once all the frames are loaded into Photoshop, the work is simple ¡V select all the layers and set the blending mode to ¡§Lighten¡¨. The same technique is used when compositing star trail images from separate 30-second exposures. I didn¡¦t want to use normal lens corrections to remove the fisheye distortion as it would pull too much of the ¡§magic¡¨ out of the frame, so I opted to use the warp tool and the liquify tool to manually straighten the horizon. This was difficult, as I needed to maintain realistic star paths in the sky, as closely resembling their normal paths as possible.
 
I had attempted a similar shot a few years ago and didn¡¦t like the results¡K but I thought I¡¦d try it again. Let me know what you think. :)?
title: Painted Heavens

description:
The Northern Lights have always fascinated me, and I feel so privileged that I had a second opportunity to photograph them on this trip. The aurora was blasting across the night sky on many occasions, sometimes obscured by cloud cover... but on clear nights the dancing sky was beautiful to watch. This is one frame that I've edited out of a time-lapse sequence.

This was shot with a fisheye lens, and the horizon line was corrected using various tools in Photoshop (mostly Warp and Liquify). I enjoy playing with the colours and details in photographs like this, bringing out the blues in the night sky without affecting the greens, all the while trying to bring out the subtle purple tones mixed in between.

These displays can be somewhat surreal to people who don't live in this region, or ordinary occurrences that are taken for granted by those that see them frequently. Even to those people who see these dancing lights as commonplace, these photos can still capture a certain "magic" that the human eye doesn't perceive.

Part of that has to do with perspective, and a 180 degree view from a fisheye lens is helpful. In my case, I had to work carefully with my lens as it was misbehaving and the aperture blades would get stuck. It's in for repairs now, but I had to find a solution in the field - shooting wide open at F/2.8 solved the problem, which in turn allows me to shoot at a faster frame-rate and freeze the dancing lights in place. F/2.8 is usually not a common aperture for landscape photographers, but fisheye lenses have an inherently greater depth of field at any given aperture.

I've only just begun digging though images that I've photographed in the past month, but I can already tell you that my travels were well worth it. :)?
title: Dancing Sky

description:
Woodland Dreams
I have had the fortune for adventure this past year, and of travels through the Yukon wilderness I was presented with a number of exceptional auroras cascading across the skies.

I¡¦ve taken a bit of a hiatus as concluding my Snowflake-a-Day project resulting in an immeasurable backlog of work, but the catch-up game is nearly won and I¡¦ve been digging through images I haven¡¦t processed for months. I can¡¦t believe that shots like this are still sitting and waiting for me.

These exposures can be difficult. Balancing light collection with depth (aperture), shutter speed with star blur and pushing sensitivity to the limits, I was able to make this image. Shot at F/4, I was at the widest aperture of my 24-105L lens, gathering as much light as possible. At 28mm, I could not extend my shutter speed beyond 15 second, or the stars would be noticeably blurring as the Earth spins. To accomplish this, I needed to shoot at ridiculously high ISO of 10,000. Still looks pretty good for pushing the limits!

The aurora was relatively faint in the night sky, allowing for a good number of stars to shine through it. The brightest auroras aren¡¦t always the most beautiful, as they tend to drown out the stars behind them.

I hope someday to travel to Northern Canada again, having made the trek twice already. Each time I feel it¡¦s the experience of a lifetime, both as a photographer and as a human being.
title: Woodland Fantasy

description:
Parc National de la Jacques-Cartier, Qu?bec, Canada - ?t? 2014

What a memorable evening! The most beautiful of my short photographic life. During the day, there were some announcements of aurora borealis. I've never seen one, so I thought that my wife and kids should come along. We spent an evening under the stars watching the northern lights. The show was worth the trip, as the lights went from magenta to green. At about 22h00, the kids fell asleep on mattresses in blankets and snowsuits and we took relaxed while the last lights we disapearing. You can see my wife and my two children, Victor and Laurence in the bottom left corner.
---
Quelle soir?e m?morable! La plus belle de ma courte vie photographique. Durant la journ?e, il y avait quelques annonces pr?voyant des aurores bor?ales. N'en ayant jamais vu, je me disait qu'il fallait vivre ?a en famille. Nous sommes donc partis passer une soir?e sous les ?toiles ? regarder les aurores. Le spectacle en vallait le d?placement, car les lumi?res passaient du magenta au vert. Vers 22h, les enfants on pu se coucher sur des matelas, dans des couvertures de polar et leurs habits de neige et nous avons profit? des derni?res lumi?res que nous voyons sur cette photo. Vous pouvez voir ma conjointe et mes deux enfants, Victor et Laurence dans le coin en bas ? gauche.
title: Aurores en famille

description: Race Point Beach in Provincetown September 12th, 2014 at 9:06PM It was a last minute venture out to attempt to photograph the Northern Lights that were projected to be seen in my part of the world, New England, Massachusetts specifically. I headed out to the most unobstructed northern horizon view, Race Point Beach in Provincetown, MA. We got there just a little too late and only snapped out a few shots that showed the lights. Minutes after this shot, the rising moon (that was off to the right of the frame) started to rise and overtook the colors and even the Milky Way that is slightly visible with the extra lights. I'll post another shot that was just a mere 4 minutes before this shot that has totally different colors. I went with this one first because you can see the people viewing the lights. I was lucky enough to even catch a galaxy in the shot. Some info on the Northern Lights: "According to AccuWeather.com Astronomer Hunter Outten, the flare is ranked as an X-class, or the highest class for a solar flare. Along with the brilliant light display that may be visible to some in the northern part of the country, a flare of this magnitude could also have adverse effects on GPS, radio frequencies and cell phone and satellite reception as well. A coronal mass ejection (CME), or a cloud of charged particles released from solar activity, is expected to induce a geomagnetic storm in Earth's atmosphere, around midday Friday. Outten said that this CME will be the second of a "two-hit punch." The geomagnetic storm will cause the northern lights show. There will be some hurdles present for some hopeful viewers, however. Outten pointed out that we're just getting out of the Supermoon, so the light will dull some of the views. There will also be some cloud coverage that will hinder views as well. Clouds will be especially problematic in the Upper Ohio Valley into the Northeast. Some clouds reaching the northern Plains may also hinder viewing conditions. Outten said that DSLR cameras will pick up the lights better than the human eye may. Solar flares create auroras when radiation from the sun reaches Earth and interacts with charged protons in our atmosphere. The effects are greater at the magnetic poles and weaken as they move south from the Arctic or north of the Antarctic. In the Northern Hemisphere, the results are called the aurora borealis, with the aurora australis being its southern counterpart. The result is a spectacular display of light and color for areas with clear enough views." SOURCE: www.accuweather.com/en/features/trend/northern_lights_vie...
title: The Solar Storm Gives Way to the Rising Moon

description:
September 12th at 9:02PM
Race Point Beach in Provincetown, Massachusetts

This one was taken just before the 86% Super Moon was rising on the east (just off to the right of the frame). I managed to get the Super Moon rising glow to the East (right), the Milky Way in the North-East, and the Solar Storm in the North. 

The color was quickly changing and was completely over come by the moon rise. Regardless, it was a awesome sight.

This was a single frame at ISO3200, f/2.8, 30 second exposure. You can see some people watching the colored light show on the bottom left.
title: Any Colour You Like

title: Late Night Hiking Adventure

description: I saw with my own eyes the Northern Lights for the first time last night. We were given an outstanding show from 20:30 to 21:00. A steady green light near the horizon was topped with pink and magenta light beams actively moving along. I wish to all of those who have never seen these landscapes to enjoy this almost surreal experience. This unforgettable evening took place at the Parc de la Jacques-Cartier, in the area of the Valley. Follow me to see what's coming next and visit www.fredbeaupre.com for prints and licensing. -------------------- J'ai pu voir de mes yeux des aurores bor?ales pour la premi?re fois hier soir. Nous avons eu droit ? tout un spectacle entre 20h30 et 21h00. Une constante lumi?re verte pr?s de l'horizon ?tait surmont?e de faisceaux lumineux rose et magenta bougeant activement. Je souhaite ? tous ceux n'ayant jamais vu ces paysages de vivre cette exp?rience presque irr?elle. Cette soir?e inoubliable s'est d?roul?e au Parc de la Jacques-Cartier, dans le secteur de la Vall?e. Suivez-moi pour voir les prochaines photos et visitez www.fredbeaupre.com pour des impressions et utilisations commerciales.
title: Aurores Bor?ales dans la Vall?e

description:
September 12, 2014, 8:46 PM

Last night we were treated with quite a short, but intense, display of northern lights across much of the northeastern United States. It was visible soon after sunset and peaked around 8:45 PM. By 9 PM it had mostly faded from view, but I continued to get some very faint color for another hour until the moonrise washed it out. This is my favorite frame of a timelapse I captured of the solar storm reflecting in the pond in my back yard. The Andromeda galaxy can be seen in the upper right.

Camera settings: 14mm, f/2.8, ISO 2500, 20 seconds, 3360¢XK white balance.

Equipment used: Nikon D700, Nikon 14-24mm f/2.8, RamperPro, eMotimo TB3 Black, Dynamic Perception Stage Zero dolly, Really Right Stuff TVC-34L tripod, BH-40 ballhead, and clamps, MeFOTO RoadTrip tripod, DewNot heat strip, DewBuster, and Goal Zero Sherpa 100 battery.
title: Aurora borealis over my back yard pond in Lee, Maine

description:
Parc National de la Jacques-Cartier, Qu?bec, Canada - ?t? 2014
#fivedayblackandwhitechallenge

I've been challenged by my friend Jack Thatcher yesterday for a five days black and white challenge. How cool is that, a whole week of b&w! My first entry for the challenge is a landscape star photography. This is the first time I try black and white with those shots. I guess I did not choose the ideal photo at first because this one was a northern lights photo (slight greenish halo above the mountains). In the end, we do not see as much stars as I would have hoped but I don't care that much. I like the shot. :)
---
J'ai ?t? d?fi? par mon ami Jack Thatcher pour produire cinq photos en noir et blanc en autant de jours. Ma premi?re soumission est une photo de ciel ?toil?. C'est la premi?re fois que je tente l'exp?rience n&b avec ce genre de paysage. Je crois par contre avoir mal choisi ma photo, car nous ne voyons pas autant d'?toiles que j'aurais voulu vu la "pollution lumineuse" des aurores bor?ales. Mais bon, il faut bien faire des exp?riences et plus je regarde la photo, plus je l'appr?cie. :)
title: D?fi N&B Jour 1 - Ciel ?toil?

description: The ancients called it the "Morning Wind" and it has amazed mankind since we first looked toward the heavens. This view of the Aurora Borealis reflected in the Chena River was taken in Fairbanks, Alaska last month. If you would like some pointers on how to photograph the Northern Lights, or would just like to see more of my images of them, check out my blog at: www.firefallphotography.com/secrets-tips-great-aurora-bor... Have a great day! Jeff My Website ? My Blog ? Google+? Facebook
title: Northern Reflections

description: The Northern Lights dance in the skies over the Chena River near Fairbanks Alaska. I had never seen the Northern Lights until the night I took this shot a few years ago. What impressed me most wasn't the sheer beauty of the spectacle...which I had sort of expected from the photos I'd seen before. What mesmerized me was the sensuous way the Lights moved...they truly danced. That was truly a delightful shock. No matter how old and jaded you might think you are, mother nature can still surprise and delight you! Jeff You can see more of my Night Sky Gallery images at: www.firefallphotography.com/night-skies-gallery/ Nikon D800E 14.0-24.0 mm f/2.8 ?/2.8 15 sec. ISO 560
title: "Twilight Tango"

description: On September 9th and 10th of 2014 there were a succession of solar flares and coronal mass ejections that were partially earth-directed. Expecting good aurora we drove out of town to the White Mountains to watch the skies on the night of September 11. While driving back from the Whites early in the morning on the 12th, the sky erupted as we neared Chatanika. We made a few stops near Cleary Summit to watch. What started as a rather drab display turned out to be one of the best shows I've seen yet. I have a few more photos from this display on my site: www.lwpetersenphotography.com/Date/2014/September/2014-09...
title: Aurora Curtain

description: A circumpolar star trail composite, shot at the old Larson Ranch site in the Frenchman Valley at Grasslands National Park, Saskatchewan, August 27/28, 2014. The pioneer cabin was the home of the legendary western author and movie star Will James, born Ernest Dufault in Quebec. He lived in this cabin when he worked the ranches in the area. The aurora was excellent this night. This is a stack of 20 1-minute exposures at ISO 2500 with the 15mm full-frame fish-eye lens at f/3.2 and the Canon 6D. The foreground and point-like stars are from the first frame in the series.
title: Aurora & Star Trails at Larson Ranch, Grasslands Park

description: The Northern Lights shot at the old Larson Ranch site in the Frenchman Valley at Grasslands National Park, Saskatchewan, August 27/28, 2014. The pioneer cabin was the home of the legendary western author and movie star Will James, born Ernest Dufault in Quebec. He lived in this cabin when he worked the ranches in the area. The aurora was excellent this night. This is a single 1-minute exposures at ISO 2500 with the 15mm full-frame fish-eye lens at f/3.2 and the Canon 6D.

description: The aurora borealis in a mild display AUgust 26/27, 2014 as shot from Grasslands National Park in Saskatchewan. This is a single frame from a 200-frame time-lapse taken with the Canon 6D and Rokinon 14mm at f/2.8 and for 60 seconds at ISO 5000, making the bright parts of the display overexposed here (shortly after this, as the aurora brightened I cut back the exposure).

title: Startrail and Aurora

description: It was totally unexpected. After we arrived at the RV park in Valdez, I went for a short walk, which turned out to be the one of best decisions I made! The best time to see Aurora in Alaska is from September to March, but it doesn't mean that you can't see Aurora during other times. As long as it is dark and the weather is good, there is always a chance to see it! This photo is one of the many captures that I used for my first time-lapse video: www.flickr.com/photos/photos_of_tao/15261510681/ The aurora is actually dancing from left to right. Inexperienced as I was for my first time lapse capture of the aurora, I set the exposure time to 10 seconds, which was way to long and a serious mistake.
title: Aurora in the sky

description: View and reflections from Brainard Lake of the Indian Peaks Wilderness area, in Boulder County Colorado with the Milky Way overhead in the Sky and a hint of green 'airglow' . This is my all time favorite place on the planet. A planned shot for a long time. We were lucky to get clear skies. The Indian Peaks Wilderness is a wilderness area located in north central Colorado, west of Boulder, managed jointly by the United States Forest Service and the National Park Service within the Arapaho and Roosevelt National Forests and small parts of the southern section of Rocky Mountain National Park. It borders the James Peak Wilderness to the south, and straddles the Continental Divide. The area receives very high visitation due to its proximity to the Boulder and Denver metropolitan area. The area encompasses a stretch of the Front Range. It includes 7 peaks over 13,000 feet (4,000 m) in elevation. The highest point is North Arapaho Peak at 13,502 feet (4,115 m). The peaks are all within 100 feet (30 m) of elevation of each other. A portion of the area, encompassing the headwaters of North Boulder Creek, is closed to the public as it is the City of Boulder watershed. Many of the peaks inside the wilderness area are named after western Native American tribes. The naming scheme was the idea of botany teacher Ellsworth Bethel. By 1914, few of the peaks between Longs Peak and the Arapaho Peaks had names. In the spring of that year Bethel, inspired by the established name of the Arapaho Peaks, settled on 11 tribal names for various summits along the Divide. The United States Board on Geographic Names kept 6 of his names: Apache Peak, Arikaree Peak, Kiowa Peak, Navajo Peak, Ogalalla Peak and Pawnee Peak. He later added Paiute Peak, as his use of the Ute band was denied due to too many other Colorado features sharing that name. Other names, including Shoshoni Peak, Hiamovi Mountain, Satanta Peak and Watanga Mountain were added later. description: An all-sky aurora with green and purple curtains, the night of June 7-8, 2014, starting up about 12:30 and going until dawn. This shot was as it declined in colour and brightness, and was taken from the old barn site near home in southern Alberta. Foreground illumination is from the aurora and ambient sky -- the Moon had set but morning dawn was coming on. The Big Dipper is above the Barn. The purple colour is from blue scatttered sunlight hitting the red tops of the auroral curtains. This was with the 16-35mm lens at f/2.8 for 20 seconds at ISO 800 with the Canon 6D.
title: Purple Aurora over Old Barn #4 (June 7-8, 2014)

description: The Northern Lights swirl and dance above the tundra in Churchill, Manitoba. Photography Tip: Night photography requires strong raw image processing skills. Polishing up this image, for example, required work in Adobe Photoshop Lightroom and DxO OpticsPro 10 Elite Edition. Lightroom handles the vast majority of the color and the contrast adjustments that all of my night images require. But DxO OpticsPro 10 offers noise reduction repair tools that are more powerful than Lightroom's equivalents. Fortunately working with both programs together is easy. If you would like to learn how to shoot and process images like this one please join me this winter for my Night Skies and the Northern Lights Photography Workshop up at the Churchill Northern Studies Centre. More details on this unique small-group night photography workshop at bit.ly/auroraphotoworkshop
title: Northern Lights Above the Tundra

description:
My human body isn't designed to handle cold temperatures. It performs optimally between 50F and 90F only. So it was no surprise that when we wanted to go to Alaska in the middle of January, I shuddered at the thought of doing photography under such sub-optimal conditions.
And on the day we landed in Fairbanks, I had experienced a temperature differential of a 100F, from 68F in San Jose to -32F there. We had decided to spend a week here mainly to experience some classic northern lights or aurora borealis. And with tonight being a clear, cloud-free night, we hastened to Cleary Summit, a vista point providing promising views of the light show.
And as the night continued, the mercury dropped even further, almost freezing! I was safe inside a well-heated cabin at the vista point, but when the light show began, it took all of my gutsy spirit to step out onto the freezing weather to capture this!

Shot at a 4s exposure at ISO 4000, F4 (auroras move quite fast)

Cleary Summit
AK USA

description:
I checked the aurora predictor site I used and it called for activity this evening. Peeking outside, I could see faint moving light to the north, even with maladjusted eyesight. So I quickly bundled up (it was -26 C) and hopped in the car to zip down to my usual north-facing lakeshore view. 

I set up very close to the shore because despite a few weeks of cold, there was still slush on the ice and I felt and heard frequent booms of the ice cracking. 

This image is a panorama comprising 8 vertical shots using my manual 24mm Bower lens which handles night shots beautifully. The lights were dancing somewhat., and pretty brihgt, so I could use nice short shutter speeds. 

Hugin didn't know how to stitch this image automatically, so I had to manually select individual stars in each image to use as control points. I'm pretty pleased with this, although I will try again with another set of shots which were darker but had more distinct aurora lines. 

I wasn't sure this shoot would work because of the waxing moon, but it lit the snow nicely.
title: Aurora Borealis Panorama

description: After a summer with very little solar storm activity, some peaks have started to occur as we move into autumn. Last week saw a night with very strong aurora activity, visible across much of North America, even as far south as Ohio and Oregon. Unfortunately, Vancouver was under complete cloud cover during that display. Last night, another burst of activity was forecast, and although the strength looked only barely high enough to be visible as far south as Vancouver, I decided to take advantage of a clear sky and new moon and see if I could capture anything. From around 9:00pm to 11:30pm, there was relatively little activity, mainly a constant but faint green glow on the horizon, almost invisible to the eye, but after 11:30pm, the display got considerably stronger, being both clearly visible to the eye and to the camera. Most of the time it stayed as a steady, twisting green on the horizon, but occasionally there were these wonderful red and purple bursts of activity higher in the sky, lighting up the area around the Big Dipper. This was photographed in a small bay in the village of Horseshoe Bay in West Vancouver, looking north towards Bowyer Island, Anvil Island, Bowen Island and Gambier Island. On the right of the shot are the west slopes of the mountains in Cypress Provincial Park. The post is one of three that appear to be the remnants of a small pier. This photo has reached #150 in Flickr Explore -- thanks to everyone for their comments and favourites! Check out my most interesting photographs!
title: Northern Lights - Explored!

description: I like coming up with new types of star trails that haven¡¦t been done before, it¡¦s challenging to think outside the box with so many creative people in this world! For about a year I¡¦ve been tinkering with various ways of presenting a rift in time/space with star trails in a spherical panorama, influenced by many scifi movies and TV shows that I¡¦ve enjoyed over the years. More recently, Interstellar got me thinking about it again and playing around with different projections of vortex star trails. Last week Sathya Narayanan of liketheocean.com/ made some of this a lot easier with his new Photoshop scripts that are quicker than manually doing this with custom macros and droplets. This is a compilation of several images shot on the night of October 8, 2013 from the North Bay of Moosehead Lake at the base of Mt. Kineo. The northern lights and sky are a single shot at 11:43 PM, the lake is a stack of 243 images from 10:22 PM to 12:41 AM for a brighter reflection, and the ¡§rift star trails¡¨ are 125 frames from a single star field shot at 9:52 PM when the northern lights were dim. I layered and masked everything in Photoshop. The RAW files were edited with Lightroom. Camera settings: 14mm, f/2.8, ISO 2500, 32 seconds for each of the photos Equipment used: Nikon D700, Nikon 14-24mm f/2.8, Promote Control, Really Right Stuff TVC-34L tripod, BH-40 ballhead, DewNot heat strip, and DewBuster controller.
title: Rift Star Trails

description:
I've never done shots like this before and I don't really know what I'm doing. Any tips would be appreciated. Adding to the difficulty for me was a considerable amount of light contamination coming from street lights behind me.

Anyway...on with the pic. This is the monument to David Thompson that overlooks Lac La Biche. Thompson was great explorer of Canada and the first known European to land in Lac La Biche in 1798. Lac La Biche went on to become an important link in the first transcontinental fur trade route.

It was a little early in the year for the northern lights, but there was just a hint of them - enough to show up with a long exposure.
title: Big Dipper and a hint of Aurora Borealis

description:
Midnight at Third Lake at Joffre Lakes Provincial Park.

The green and purple colors in the sky were not visible to my eye.  The purple appeared in only one photo.  Here it is.  I am guessing it might be the Northern Lights?     Comments welcomed.  

Wild fires in the area sent smoke south into Vancouver and Washington State earlier in the summer.  I headed south and into Eastern Washington to avoid this smoke.   We ended up here this weekend because the smoke in Eastern Washington and the Cascades was too thick.  It has been a bad summer for tires.  We were happy for clear blue skies.  Or, clear purple and green skies.

You can find more of my Milky Way photos here and more of my Northern Lights photos here. Feeling social? You can also find me on: facebook | google+ | tumblr | instagram | 500px | elmofoto.com _________________________________________________ You know, I've been sitting on this series since early August. Why? Well, I wasn't sure how to process these photos because, well, I don't do a lot of star photography and I've never had the fortune of having the Northern Lights in one of my shots, especially not in such vivid colors. But how am I ever going to get better at processing these if I don't upload them and solicit your opinion? So, feel free to share, especially if you have a preferred method of handling the aurora part of the shot. I may go back and reprocess this some time down the road when I'm better at these kinds of shots, but for now let's go with this one. Thanks in advance to anyone who feels compelled to put in their two cents. A little background: on the evening that I shot this (and also this shot), I didn't realize that what looked like a fog bank off to the northwest over the lake was actually the Northern Lights. They were really faint and looked almost white. In retrospect I should have probably figured out that a fog bank would never appear so white and bright from such a distance, but I sure did think it was fog :) Anyway, when I saw what i thought was fog coming in, I figured I'd better start shooting the Milky Way before we were under cloud cover. I took a few southerly shots of the Milky Way and then turned to catch the north-facing view. I set my first exposure for 15 seconds and when I checked the camera back for the histogram I noticed the violet and green streaks on the bottom. I knew immediately what it was looking at, but still couldn't quite believe it. A few moments later it fully sunk in and it is alleged by my girlfriend and cousins, who were out there making smores, that I might have dropped an F-bomb and done a little happy dance. All alleged, mind you :) I hope your day is going well! -Lorenzo

description:
A magnetic storm this weekend promised a good chance of an Aurora Borealis sighting. On Friday and Saturday the forecast was fairly steady but quite low, and being relatively far south in Vancouver, BC, the chances of a good show seemed unlikely.

Last night, the forecast showed the possibility of some spikes of activity in the early hours of the morning, so I figured what better way to break in the 5D Mark III Mark II! As I've not yet got a shot I'm totally happy with from this location, I again headed to Porteau Cove Provincial Park, about 30 minutes drive north of Vancouver.

For most of the evening, the Aurora was steady and visible, but very low on the horizon, not making for the best photography opportunity. However, there were two occasions where we saw a significant spike in activity, which caused the sky to light up! The peak of activity in both cases lasted for only about 60 seconds, and had died back down to low level activity after 5 minutes.

This capture shows the second of the two peaks in aurora activity.  This is a 5-shot panorama at 24mm, as my 16-35mm lens is still away with the Canon medics.
title: Purple Aurora

Facebook

description:
On a clear night in the high Sierra two friends set out on a lake a mile above sea level to watch the stars. They found the universe gazing back at them. I was lucky to grab this image of a great friend of mine gazing at the Milky Way. I think we both were  awestruck by the grandiose beauty of the scene unfolding before us as the center of the galaxy glistened above, reflections of twinkling stars danced along the surface of Gerle Creek reservoir. We were deep in the Crystal Basin Recreation area of California's El Dorado National Forest about an hour from civilization and nestled in a basin of mountains shielding the sky from oppressive light pollution. The orange glow along the horizon is light from  Sacramento 50 miles+ to the south west. It was so dark the stars were the only light source besides headlamps, and flashlights lol. I was so happy to make this image and astounded by the shear beauty of nature but most important was the moment captured in this scene. I wanted to show the beauty of that moment someone sees the night sky in its grandeur and time stops as they gaze the heavens above.

description: The Big Dipper (obviously enhanced) and the tail end of the Milky Way on the right.
About 15 seconds into this exposure I slowly started zooming in for the last half of the exposure.
Northern Lights fading...
This was about the best I could catch of the Northern Lights around 1:09 AM. The north end of the Milky Way is in the upper right.
Caught a shooting star...

Wow! Highest Position Explore #14 July 31, 2013 Thank You! www.davidrironsjrphotography.com Okay...I will wait as my Flickr friends pick themselves up off the ground! I know...another post! I have not been out shooting much this Summer because I have been so busy at work and...uh...well the skies have been too clear for me to get anything exciting! That is...until I found this great website(that one of my friends hooked me up with) that shows the Aurora Borealis activity (website: www.softservenews.com/Aurora.htm ) I have always wanted to see and capture the Northern Lights and I live at a latitude which can sometimes afford us a glimpse. The Seattle area is far enough north which does allow us to see it's southern reaches. What is amazing here is that I am essentially in the middle of the city and I could capture one of Mother Nature's most beautiful sights! This is a single RAW image which I processed in Photoshop RAW. The exposure is around 4 minutes long and I shot at a smaller aperture, than I normally would shoot stars with. I shot at the smaller aperture so the light from the lighthouse would create a little bit of a star burst effect. I also "Light Painted" the grass in the foreground and the sides of the lighthouse with my headlamp for about 8 seconds. I shot this at 1600ISO, so you can imagine the ton of noise I got, so I ran through Topaz DeNoise. When that did not get it all, I went down to three pixels and cloned out the specks of noise...Yes that was tedious but worth it. Once again, thank you to all of my Flickr friends for your support, views, comments and faves. I really appreciate them! Please do not use my images on blogs or websites without my permission. I own the copyright on all RAW and final processed images. All images are available for license through either Getty Images or for sale or license through my website and direct inquiry. Thank you.

description:
We got the Aurora Watch Red Alert message around 9:10 PM, the first time we've had one on a clear night in a long time around here.

We didn't want to drive too far to get shots, so I found a little acerage subdivision north of Sherwood Park that would be reasonably dark.  We waited around for about an hour, with nothing to see except a pretty awesome sunset, but no auroras, so we packed up and started to go.

We hadn't driven more than a minute when the sky expoded in front of us with one of the most amazing aurora displays I have yet seen.  We quickly drove back to the acerage, unpacked, and took a few shots.  The display only lasted maybe 10 minutes, but we weren't disappointed.  It was an amazing sight.

The glow on the horizon is the city glow of Edmonton.  Given how bright that is, it should help emphasize how bright these auroras were.
title: Aurora Red Alert

description:
As some of you are no doubt aware, we are currently approaching a solar maximum, a peak in the activity of the Sun which results in, amongst other things, stronger solar winds. These peaks in the Sun's activity occur approximately every 11 years, and the geomagnetic storms that are usually only visible in the far north or south can, in the right conditions, be seen over a much larger area.

The strength of geomagnetic storms is measured using the Kp index, a numeric value from 0-9. Around Vancouver, a value of 4 is required to be able to see the aurora on the horizon, and a value of 6 means that it will be visible overhead (in the correct, dark-sky conditions, of course).

Accordingly, when I saw a value of 7.3 forecast at the end of May, the highest value I've seen since I've been actively monitoring the forecast, I figured that I had to go out and see what I could get, despite a persistent thin layer of cloud which looked like it would be my undoing. I didn't expect to get much, but I knew if I didn't try, and saw someone else's shot, I would be kicking myself!

I arrived at my favourite star observation spot, Porteau Cove Provincial Park, at about 11:30, and it was immediately clear that despite the cloud, there was definitely some aurora visibility -- a very noticeable blue-green glow was on the horizon to the north, which I was pretty certain wasn't the result of the Squamish lights!

While we never did get clear viewing conditions, as can be seen by the relatively few visible stars, the brightness of the lights on the horizon did vary. This is a 7-shot panorama taken from one of the viewing platforms at Porteau Cove Provincial Park, although I've cropped it down at the edges. This nicely captures the green glow of the aurora through the clouds and its reflection on the water, as well as the odd patterns in the sky to the west, I believe caused by thin layers of cloud reflecting the lights of Gibsons and Nanaimo.

Edit: The column structure to the west is actually an atmospheric phenomenon known as a light pillar!

I am very hopeful that another strong storm forecast will coincide with clear, dark skies this year, but I'm also glad that I took the chance and went out to capture this -- even though the conditions were not ideal, it was stunning to see and photograph.

This photo has reached #172 in Flickr Explore -- thanks to everyone for their comments and favourites!
title: Aurora Borealis at Porteau Cove - Explored!

description: Another image from our trip to Fairbanks this winter. This one has been in my to-do bucket for some time. I had two camera bodies both running on intervalometers doing back-to-back exposures. The idea was to have sequences that could be used for time-lapse, star trails, and individual frames. The concept worked well. The interesting thing about auroras is that they "stack" or combine in the image the same way the stars do. Each frame paints a layer onto the final image. This shot is from my Canon 50D with the Canon 16-35mm f/2.8L II on it. It was facing east, which is where the auroras had originated the first two nights. The glow to the right is from both the rising moon (behind clouds) and the city lights from Fairbanks reflecting off the clouds. This image is a stack from 182 images, each shot at f/2.8, 16mm, 13 seconds. There are over 400 images in this sequence that I used for my time-lapse video, but many of the frames had planes or really bright auroras that distracted from a stacked image. This middle 182 images seemed to give the best composition. The time-lapse movie can be seen here: vimeo.com/63274880

description: This pano was made from 12 vertical shots stitched together in Photoshop (elements). I'd love some suggestions for improving this next time around. There are some things I know don't work: the light pollution in the center, under the arch, also the upper portion of the image has stars that are stretched and distorted. Does anyone know if a different stitching software (such as AutoPano Pro) would do a better job with the outer portion of the images? Thanks for any help.
title: Milky Way Arch

description:
An artist set up a light show to re-create the "Northern Lights" (usually only seen in the northern most parts of the hemisphere) on the outside of the Kennedy Center. This is an 8.0 second timed exposure pic of the front of the Kennedy Center with the "Northern  Lights" display in full swing.

Froze my butt off for these pics as the wind was quite strong and cold. The reflecting pool was very choppy due to the wind but as the picture had a long exposure, it gave the water a smoother matte appearance.
title: Northern Lights display 1

description: It felt a little like I imagine winning the lottery feels like. (I wouldn't know, I never buy a ticket.) I was working hard to get the angle right to encompass the setting Milky Way, the foreground interest, the island, and the edge of the faint aurora. It just so happened that once I got the composition I wanted, my very next 30 second exposure captured this bright meteor. I had to clone out a streak of light from a passing plane, but I was very pleased with the final result here. It was worth the -23 temperature and the soaker from breaking through the ice along the shore (how can it still not be solid?!)
title: Night Sky Trifecta

description: A dazzling display of the northern lights (aurora borealis) erupted on November 13th/14th.  Even though it was considered a moderate geomagnetic storm (KP 6), it was one of the best light shows I have seen in years.  I did have a tense moment, however, as anywhere from 5 to 8 coyotes closed in on me to about twenty five yards or so. They decided to take off, yelping all the way through the field back into the forest.  Clarence-Rockland, Ontario.
